# Dictionary to store mapping of code to text

# Path and filename for exporting
export_path = 'D://reva project 2024//normalized_tables//n4//'
export_filename = f'mapping_to_excel_{timestamp}.xlsx'

# Create an Excel writer object
excel_writer = pd.ExcelWriter(export_path + export_filename, engine='xlsxwriter')

# Iterate over each column
for col in df99.columns:
    # Check if the column is categorical
    if df99[col].dtype == 'object':
        # Get unique text values and their codes
        unique_values = df99[col].unique()
        # Create mapping
        mapping[col] = {i: text for i, text in enumerate(unique_values)}
        # Print mapping for the column
        print(f"Column: {col}")
        print("Code\tText")
        for code, text in mapping[col].items():
            print(f"{code}\t{text}")
        print()
        # Create mapping DataFrame
        mapping_df = pd.DataFrame({col: unique_values})
        # Set the column header as the sheet name and export to Excel
        mapping_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name=col, index_label='Code')
        print(f"Mapping for column '{col}' exported.",export_filename)

# Save the Excel file
excel_writer.save()
excel_writer.close()

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from datetime import datetime
from pandas.api.types import is_sparse

def column_analysis(df):
    # Create a list to store the analysis results for each column
    analysis_results = []
    
    # Get total number of rows in the DataFrame
    total_rows = len(df)
    
    # Iterate over each column of the DataFrame
    for column in df.columns:
        # Determine the data type of the column
        data_type = df[column].dtype
        
        # Initialize variables for statistical analysis
        mean = median = mode = minimum = maximum = std_dev = lowest_positive = None
        
        # Calculate the number of unique values in the column
        num_unique_values = df[column].nunique()
        
        # Count the number of blanks and non-blanks in the column
        num_blanks = df[column].isnull().sum()
        num_non_blanks = total_rows - num_blanks
        
        if is_sparse(data_type):
            # For sparse columns
            # Convert sparse column to dense array
            dense_column = df[column].sparse.to_dense()
            
            if np.issubdtype(dense_column.dtype, np.number):
                # For numeric columns
                mean = dense_column.mean()
                median = dense_column.median()
                mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
                minimum = dense_column.min()
                maximum = dense_column.max()
                std_dev = dense_column.std()
                
                # Find the lowest positive value in the column
                lowest_positive = dense_column[dense_column > 0].min()
            else:
                # For non-numeric columns (assume strings)
                mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
        elif np.issubdtype(data_type, np.number):
            # For numeric columns
            column_data = df[column]
            mean = column_data.mean()
            median = column_data.median()
            mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
            minimum = column_data.min()
            maximum = column_data.max()
            std_dev = column_data.std()
            
            # Find the lowest positive value in the column
            lowest_positive = column_data[column_data > 0].min()
        else:
            # For non-numeric columns (assume strings)
            mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
        
        # Append analysis results to the list
        analysis_results.append({
            'Column Name': column,
            'Data Type': data_type,
            'Mean': mean,
            'Median': median,
            'Mode': mode,
            'Min': minimum,
            'Max': maximum,
            'Standard Deviation': std_dev,
            'Lowest Positive': lowest_positive,
            'Number of Unique Values': num_unique_values,
            'Number of Blanks': num_blanks,
            'Number of Non-Blanks': num_non_blanks,
            'Total Rows': total_rows
        })
    
    # Create a DataFrame from the list of analysis results
    analysis_df = pd.DataFrame(analysis_results)
    
    timestamp = datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M-%S")
    export_path = 'D://reva project 2024//normalized_tables//n4//'
    
    # Export the analysis DataFrame to an Excel file
    export_filename = f'column_analysis_{timestamp}.xlsx'
    analysis_df.to_excel(export_path + export_filename, index=False)
    print(f"Column analysis exported to '{export_filename}'.")

    # Select only valid numeric columns for summary statistics
    numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
    
    # Create a DataFrame for summary statistics
    summary_stats = pd.DataFrame({
        'Count': numeric_columns.count(),
        'Mean': numeric_columns.mean(),
        'Median': numeric_columns.median(),
        'Mode': numeric_columns.mode().iloc[0],
        'Min': numeric_columns.min(),
        'Max': numeric_columns.max(),
        'Standard Deviation': numeric_columns.std(),
        'Lowest Positive': numeric_columns[numeric_columns > 0].min(),
        'Number of Unique Values': numeric_columns.nunique()
    })
    
    export_filename = f'summary_stats_{timestamp}.xlsx'
    # Export the summary statistics DataFrame to an Excel file
    summary_stats.to_excel(export_path + export_filename)
    print(f"Summary statistics exported to '{export_filename}'.")

# Example usage:
# Assuming you have a DataFrame named df_for_column_analysis
# Call the function with your DataFrame
# column_analysis(df_for_column_analysis)
# column_analysis(df)
column_analysis(combined_df)

        mean = median = mode = minimum = maximum = std_dev = lowest_positive = None
        
        # Calculate the number of unique values in the column
        num_unique_values = df[column].nunique()
        
        # Count the number of blanks and non-blanks in the column
        num_blanks = df[column].isnull().sum()
        num_non_blanks = total_rows - num_blanks
        
        if is_sparse(data_type):
            # For sparse columns
            # Convert sparse column to dense array
            dense_column = df[column].sparse.to_dense()
            
            if np.issubdtype(dense_column.dtype, np.number):
                # For numeric columns
                mean = dense_column.mean()
                median = dense_column.median()
                mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
                minimum = dense_column.min()
                maximum = dense_column.max()
                std_dev = dense_column.std()
                
                # Find the lowest positive value in the column
                lowest_positive = dense_column[dense_column > 0].min()
            else:
                # For non-numeric columns (assume strings)
                mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
        elif np.issubdtype(data_type, np.number):
            # For numeric columns
            column_data = df[column]
            mean = column_data.mean()
            median = column_data.median()
            mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
            minimum = column_data.min()
            maximum = column_data.max()
            std_dev = column_data.std()
            
            # Find the lowest positive value in the column
            lowest_positive = column_data[column_data > 0].min()
        else:
            # For non-numeric columns (assume strings)
            mode = df[column].mode()[0] if not df[column].empty and not df[column].isnull().all() else None
        
        # Calculate the correlation with the column 'Bene_Avg_Risk_Scre'
        correlation_with_target = df[column].corr(df['Bene_Avg_Risk_Scre'])
        
        # Append analysis results to the list
        analysis_results.append({
            'Column Name': column,
            'Data Type': data_type,
            'Mean': mean,
            'Median': median,
            'Mode': mode,
            'Min': minimum,
            'Max': maximum,
            'Standard Deviation': std_dev,
            'Lowest Positive': lowest_positive,
            'Number of Unique Values': num_unique_values,
            'Number of Blanks': num_blanks,
            'Number of Non-Blanks': num_non_blanks,
            'Total Rows': total_rows,
            'Correlation with Bene_Avg_Risk_Scre': correlation_with_target
        })
    
    # Create a DataFrame from the list of analysis results
    analysis_df = pd.DataFrame(analysis_results)
    
    timestamp = datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M-%S")
    export_path = 'D://reva project 2024//normalized_tables//n4//'
    
    # Export the analysis DataFrame to an Excel file
    export_filename = f'column_analysis_{timestamp}.xlsx'
    analysis_df.to_excel(export_path + export_filename, index=False)
    print(f"Column analysis exported to '{export_filename}'.")

    # Select only valid numeric columns for summary statistics
    numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
    
    # Create a DataFrame for summary statistics
    summary_stats = pd.DataFrame({
        'Count': numeric_columns.count(),
        'Mean': numeric_columns.mean(),
        'Median': numeric_columns.median(),
        'Mode': numeric_columns.mode().iloc[0],
        'Min': numeric_columns.min(),
        'Max': numeric_columns.max(),
        'Standard Deviation': numeric_columns.std(),
        'Lowest Positive': numeric_columns[numeric_columns > 0].min(),
        'Number of Unique Values': numeric_columns.nunique(),
        'Correlation with Bene_Avg_Risk_Scre': numeric_columns.apply(lambda x: x.corr(df['Bene_Avg_Risk_Scre']))
    })
    
    export_filename = f'summary_stats_{timestamp}.xlsx'
    # Export the summary statistics DataFrame to an Excel file
    summary_stats.to_excel(export_path + export_filename)
    print(f"Summary statistics exported to '{export_filename}'.")

# To incrementally add to the learning of a machine learning model stored in a pickle file, you would typically follow these steps:

# Load the existing model from the pickle file.
# Train the loaded model with new data or additional iterations.
# Save the updated model back to the pickle file.

import pickle

# Step 1: Load the existing model from the pickle file
try:
    with open('model.pkl', 'rb') as file:
        existing_model = pickle.load(file)
except FileNotFoundError:
    # Handle the case where the file doesn't exist yet
    existing_model = None

# Step 2: Train the model with new data or additional iterations
# Example: Assuming you have new training data 'X_new' and corresponding labels 'y_new'
if existing_model is not None:
    # Assuming you have a function 'train_model' to train the model
    existing_model = train_model(existing_model, X_new, y_new)
else:
    # If there's no existing model, create and train a new one
    existing_model = train_initial_model(X_new, y_new)

# Step 3: Save the updated model back to the pickle file
with open('model.pkl', 'wb') as file:
    pickle.dump(existing_model, file)

# parallel processing capabilities. We'll parallelize the training and evaluation of machine learning models across different

import pickle
from datetime import datetime
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, learning_curve
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score, mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVR
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from joblib import Parallel, delayed

# Initialize regression models
models = {
    "Linear Regression": LinearRegression(),
    "Polynomial Regression": None,  # Placeholder for polynomial regression
    "Support Vector Regression": SVR(kernel='rbf'),
    "Decision Tree Regression": DecisionTreeRegressor(),
    "Random Forest Regression": RandomForestRegressor(),
    "Gradient Boosting Regression": GradientBoostingRegressor(),
    "Neural Network Regression": MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=(100,), max_iter=1000)
}

# Define a list of test sizes to iterate over
test_sizes = [0.2, 0.3, 0.4]

# Initialize DataFrames to store data
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'MSE', 'R-squared', 'MAE', 'Cross-Validation Mean MSE', 'Test Size'])
feature_importance_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Feature', 'Importance', 'Model', 'Test Size'])
scatter_plot_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Test Size', 'Actual Values', 'Predicted Values'])
residual_plot_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Test Size', 'Predicted Values', 'Residuals'])
learning_curve_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Test Size', 'Training Set Size', 'Training Error', 'Cross-validation Error'])

def train_evaluate_model(name, model, X_train_scaled, X_test_scaled, X_train_poly, X_test_poly, y_train, y_test, test_size):
    print(f"Training {name}...for test size: {test_size}", datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d  %H-%M-%S"))

    # Train model
    if name == "Polynomial Regression":
        model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_poly)
    else:
        model.fit(X_train_scaled if name != "Polynomial Regression" else X_train_poly, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled if name != "Polynomial Regression" else X_test_poly)

    # Evaluate model
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    cv_mean_mse = cv_scores.mean()

    # Extract feature importance for tree-based models
    feature_importance = None
    if name == "Random Forest Regression" or name == "Decision Tree Regression":
        feature_importance = model.feature_importances_

    return {
        'Model': name,
        'MSE': mse,
        'R-squared': r2,
        'MAE': mae,
        'Cross-Validation Mean MSE': cv_mean_mse,
        'Feature Importance': feature_importance,
        'Test Size': test_size
    }

# Train and evaluate each model for each test size
for test_size in test_sizes:
    print(f"Running for test size: {test_size}", datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d  %H-%M-%S"))

    # Split data into train and test sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=42)

    # Initialize scaler outside the loop for reuse
    scaler = StandardScaler()

    # Standardize features
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

    # Initialize polynomial features outside the loop for reuse
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train_scaled)
    X_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test_scaled)

    # Use parallel processing to train and evaluate models
    results = Parallel(n_jobs=-1)(delayed(train_evaluate_model)(name, model, X_train_scaled, X_test_scaled, X_train_poly, X_test_poly, y_train, y_test, test_size)
                                   for name, model in models.items())

    # Store results in DataFrame
    for result in results:
        metrics_df = metrics_df.append(result, ignore_index=True)

    # Print model evaluation metrics
    print(metrics_df)

    # Save trained models
    for result in results:
        name = result['Model']
        model = models[name]
        timestamp = datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M-%S")
        model_file_name = f"{name.lower().replace(' ', '_')}_model_{test_size}_{timestamp}.pkl"
        with open(model_file_name, 'wb') as file:
            pickle.dump(model, file)
        print(f"{name} model saved as {model_file_name}\n")

# added ensemble methods
# To include ensemble methods such as averaging predictions from multiple models or using techniques like stacking, you can follow these steps within your existing code:

# Train Multiple Models: Train multiple regression models using different algorithms or hyperparameters. In addition to the models you've already trained, you can add more models to the models dictionary.

# Make Predictions: After training the models, make predictions on the test set for each model.

# Combine Predictions: Combine the predictions from multiple models using ensemble methods like averaging or stacking.

# Evaluate Ensemble Models: Evaluate the performance of the ensemble models using the same evaluation metrics you've used for individual models.

# Compare Performance: Compare the performance of individual models with ensemble models to determine which approach yields the best results.

from sklearn.ensemble import VotingRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score, mean_absolute_error
import numpy as np

# Initialize an empty list to store individual model predictions
individual_predictions = []

# Train and evaluate each model for each test size
for test_size in test_sizes:
    print(f"Running for test size: {test_size}", datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H-%M-%S"))
    
    # Split data into train and test sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=42)
    
    # Convert DataFrame to dense numpy arrays
    X_train_array = X_train.to_numpy()
    X_test_array = X_test.to_numpy()

    # Standardize features
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_array)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test_array)

    # Initialize a list to store individual models
    individual_models = []

    # Train and evaluate each model
    for name, model in models.items():  
        print(f"Training {name}... for test size: {test_size}", datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H-%M-%S"))

        # Train model
        if name == "Polynomial Regression":
            poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
            X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train_scaled)
            X_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test_scaled)
            model = LinearRegression()
            model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test_poly)
        else:
            model.fit(X_train_scaled if name != "Polynomial Regression" else X_train_poly, y_train)
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled if name != "Polynomial Regression" else X_test_poly)
        
        # Save individual predictions
        individual_predictions.append(y_pred)

        # Evaluate model
        mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
        r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
        mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
        cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
        cv_mean_mse = cv_scores.mean()

        # Print model evaluation metrics
        print('Model:', name,
              'MSE:', mse,
              'R-squared:', r2,
              'MAE:', mae,
              'Cross-Validation Mean MSE:', cv_mean_mse,
              'Test Size:', test_size)

        # Append the trained model to individual_models list
        individual_models.append((name, model))

    # Ensemble Methods: Averaging Predictions
    # Combine predictions from individual models
    ensemble_predictions = np.mean(individual_predictions, axis=0)
    
    # Evaluate ensemble predictions
    ensemble_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, ensemble_predictions)
    ensemble_r2 = r2_score(y_test, ensemble_predictions)
    ensemble_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, ensemble_predictions)
    
    # Print ensemble model evaluation metrics
    print('Ensemble Model:',
          'MSE:', ensemble_mse,
          'R-squared:', ensemble_r2,
          'MAE:', ensemble_mae,
          'Test Size:', test_size)
    
    # Append evaluation metrics to metrics_df for ensemble model
    metrics_df = metrics_df.append({
        'Model': 'Ensemble',
        'MSE': ensemble_mse,
        'R-squared': ensemble_r2,
        'MAE': ensemble
